I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation to be able to create connections with artists, without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We were at a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We immersed ourselves directly in things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't that easy to determine.
Without having a reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become foundations for our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where each person watches at their own pace, starting social media publications with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specific closed locations.
Unconsciously, I am dying to reconnect with the universal community that surrounded all this
That's why we are so many watching with obsession series like The Office or movies like Présentateur vedette, with plenty of short references, like memes.
We repeated these refs, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there are just too many things to see and no way to rationalize everything... will we escape hypersaturation?
we get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we're forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we enter into parasocial relationships with more attention.
We understand that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without stepping on others along the way.
Lacking collective awareness of the media, we've developed a class consciousness that helps us stay critical.
Some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We're in a turbulent period, and I'm eager to see where this will take us.
